<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-04">
  <title>Week 4</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-hausdorff">
      <title>Separation of points</title>
      <p>
        Not all spaces are created equally. Let's briefly adopt the frame that the open neighborhoods of a point <m>x</m> in a 
        space <m>X</m> — that is, all <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m> open — form a sort of microscope: ordered by inclusion, they form 
        a microscope with which we can zoom in on <m>x</m>. Being as familiar as we are with Euclidean space and optical 
        microscopes, we would expect that given <m>y\ne x\in X</m>, we should be able to zoom in far enough so that <m>y</m> 
        leaves the frame. In fact, if we aim one microscope at <m>x</m> and another microscope at <m>y</m>, then we should be 
        able to zoom in with both so that their images do not overlap, right? Right?
      </p>
      <p>
        Alas — this is not the case. For instance, if <m>X</m> has the concrete topology, then our microscope is terrible: it 
        literally cannot zoom further than viewing all of <m>X</m> at once. More formally, we cannot find open sets 
        <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m> and <m>y\in V\subseteq X</m> for which <m>U\cap V = \varnothing</m>. When we <alert>can</alert> 
        zoom in in this fashion, we say that <m>X</m> <term>separates points</term> (or is a <term>Hausdorff space</term>).
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-separate-points">
        <title>Separates points</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topological space <m>X</m> <term>separates points</term> (or is <term>Hausdorff</term>) :iff for all distinct 
            <m>x,y\in X</m> there exist open sets <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m> and <m>y\in V\subseteq X</m> that are disjoint 
            (<m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <title>Metric spaces are Hausdorff</title>
        <p>
          Most topology courses spend substantial time developing metric topology, but I have the sense that you have learned 
          or will soon learn this flavor of topology in analysis. Briefly, a <term>metric space</term> is a set <m>X</m> together with a <term>metric</term> 
          <m>d\colon X\times X\to \mathbb R_{\ge 0}</m> satisfying the following properties:
          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>identity of indiscernibles</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,y)=0</m> if and only if <m>x=y</m>,
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>symmetry</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,y)=d(y,x)</m> for all <m>x,y\in X</m>,
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>triangle inequality</title>
              <p>
                <m>d(x,z)\le d(x,y)+d(y,z)</m> for all <m>x,y,z\in X</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
          A metric space <m>(X,d)</m> carries a canonical topology generated by a basis of open balls
          <md>
            \mathscr B := \{B(x,r)\mid x\in X, r\gt 0\}
          </md>
          where <m>B(x,r):= \{y\in X\mid d(x,y)\lt r\}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We now demonstrate that the topology associated with a metric separates points. Let <m>x,y</m> be distinct points of 
          <m>X</m>. By identity of indiscernibles, <m>d(x,y)=R\gt 0</m>. Set <m>U = B(x,R/2),V=B(y,R/2)</m> and suppose 
          for contradiction that <m>z\in U\cap V</m>. Then, by the triangle inequality,
          <md>
            d(x,y)\le d(x,z)+d(z,y)\lt R/2+R/2=R,
          </md>
          contradicting <m>d(x,y)=R</m>, so in fact <m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>. These sets are open neighborhoods of <m>x,y</m>, 
          respectively, in the metric topology, so the metric topology on <m>X</m> separates points.
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        Metric spaces provide a rich class of topologies that separate points, but we can also make som staightforward 
        constructions that fail to do so.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>The line with two origins does not separate points</title>
        <p>
          Let <m>X</m> denote the pushout of the span <m>\mathbb R\leftarrow \mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}\to \mathbb R</m> in 
          which both maps are the usual inclusion of <m>\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> into <m>\mathbb R</m>. We should think 
          of <m>X</m> as a (real) line with two origins: the quotient of <m>\mathbb R\amalg \mathbb R</m> that constructs <m>X</m> 
          identifies <m>(x,0)</m> with <m>(x,1)</m> for all <m>x\ne 0</m>, but <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(0,1)</m> remain distinct.
        </p>
        <p>
          We claim that the pushout topology on <m>X</m> fails to separate the two origins. You will prove as much in your homework 
          via careful consideration of the canonical map <m>X\to \mathbb R</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        Thankfully, point separation is preserved a number of our favorite constructions.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-sep-constr">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The property of separating points is inherited by the subspace, product, and coproduct topologies.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      We'll cover a hodgepodge of topics today, namely closures, limit points, and more on sequences.
    </p>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-limit-points">
      <title>Closure and limit points</title>
      <p>
        Recall that the <term>closure</term> <m>\bar A</m> of a subset <m>A\subseteq X</m> of a space <m>X</m> is the smallest closed 
        subset of <m>X</m> containing <m>A</m>. Since arbitrary intersections of closed sets are closed, this is equivalent to 
        <md>
          \bar A = \bigcap_{\substack{A\subseteq C\subseteq X\\ C\text{ closed in }X}C.
        </md>
        Here is a deeper fact about closures:
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-in-closure">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given a subset <m>A\subseteq X</m> of a space <m>X</m>, a point <m>x</m> is in <m>\bar A</m> if and only if 
            for each open neighborhood <m>U\subseteq X</m> of <m>x</m>, <m>U\cap A</m> is nonempty.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The point <m>x</m> is in <m>\bar A</m> if and only if each closed set <m>C\supseteq A</m> contains <m>x</m>. 
          Taking complements, we see that this is true if and only if for each open set <m>U\subseteq X</m> with 
          <m>U\cap A = \varnothing</m>, we have <m>x\not\in U</m>. Taking the contrapositive, this in turn is the case if and only if for each 
          open <m>U\subseteq X</m> with <m>x\in U</m>, <m>U\cap A\ne \varnothing</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        Based on this characterization of closure, we make the following definition.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-limit-point">
        <title>Limits points and the derived set</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A\subseteq X</m> be a subset of a space <m>X</m>. A <term>limit point</term> (of <m>A</m> in 
            <m>X</m>) is an element <m>x\in X</m> for which, for each open neighborhood <m>x\in U\subseteq X</m>, 
            <md>
              (U\smallsetminus \{x\})\cap A\ne \varnothing.
            </md>
            The <term>derived set</term> (of <m>A</m> in <m>X</m>), denoted <m>A'</m>, is the set of limit points 
            of <m>A</m> in <m>X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The following lemma is immediate based on the preceding results and definition.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-closure-limit-points">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A\subseteq X</m> be a subset of a space <m>X</m>. Then
            <md>
              \bar A = A\cup A'.
            </md>
            It follows that <m>A</m> is closed if and only if it contains all its limit points.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-more-sequences">
      <title>Sequences and limits</title>
      <p>
        Recall that a <term>sequence</term> <m>\mathbf x=(x_i)</m> valued in <m>X</m> is a function <m>\mathbf x\colon \mathbb N\to X</m> 
        with <m>\mathbf x(i) = x_i</m>. A sequence <m>\mathbf x</m> in a space <m>X</m> <term>converges</term> to <m>L\in X</m> :iff 
        for all open neighborhoods <m>U\subseteq X</m> of <m>L</m>, there exists <m>N\in \mathbb N</m> such that 
        <m>i\gt N</m> implies <m>x_i\in U</m>. If the topology on <m>X</m> is generated by a basis <m>\mathscr B</m>, 
        it suffices to check this condition on basic open neighborhoods of <m>L</m>.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>Sequences with multiple limits</title>
        <p>
          Consider a set <m>X</m> with the concrete topology (so only <m>\varnothing</m> and <m>X</m> as open subsets). 
          Let <m>\mathbf x</m> be a sequence in <m>X</m> and let <m>y</m> be an arbitrary point of <m>X</m>. Then <m>\mathbf x</m> 
          converges to <m>y</m>. In particular, limits of sequences need not be unique!
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        It is no doubt distressing to encounter sequences with more than one limit. Thankfully, there is a nice condition on spaces 
        guaranteeing that a sequence has at most one limit.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-unique-limit">
        <title>Limits in spaces that separate points are unique</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is a space that separates points and that <m>\mathbf x</m> is a sequence in <m>X</m>. Then 
            <m>\mathbf x</m> has at most one limit in <m>X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>\mathbf x</m> converges to <m>L</m> and that <m>y\in X</m> is distinct from <m>L</m>. It suffices to show 
          that <m>\mathbf x</m> does not converge to <m>y</m>. Because <m>X</m> separates points, we can choose <m>L\in U,y\in V</m> 
          open subsets of <m>X</m> with <m>U\cap V=\varnothing</m>. Since <m>\mathbf x</m> converges to <m>L</m>, we know that all 
          but finitely many <m>x_i\in U</m>. Then since <m>U,V</m> are disjoint, at most finitely many <m>x_i</m>'s belong to <m>V</m>, 
          whence <m>\mathbf x</m> does not converge to <m>y</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
      </subsubsection>
      <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-seq-cts">
        <title>Sequences, closure, and continuity</title>
      <p>
        We conclude today by exploring the relationship between sequences, closure, and continuity. To make appropriate statements, we need the following 
        definition.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-metrizable">
        <title>Metrizable spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A space <m>(X,\tau)</m> is called <term>metrizable</term> :iff there exists a metric <m>d</m> on <m>X</m> with induced topology equal 
            <m>\tau</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        I will now state two lemmas which you should try to prove with your peers in class.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-seq-closure">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A\subseteq X</m> be a subset of a space <m>X</m>. Suppose <m>\mathbf a = (a_i)\colon \mathbb N\to A</m> is a sequence in <m>A</m> 
            that converges to <m>L\in X</m>. Then <m>L\in \bar A</m>, the closure of <m>A</m>. Conversely, if <m>X</m> is metrizable, then every element 
            of <m>\bar A</m> is the limit of some sequence in <m>A</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>

    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
  </subsection>
</section>
